---
title: Cheesy Smashed Burgers with Old Bay Fries, Caramelized Onion & Special Sauce
description: These burgers are sure to be a smash hit. The secret is all in the texture—the crispy, craggy edges, achieved when balls of ground beef are pressed down in a hot pan with a spatula to create super-thin, crispy burgers. Topped with gooey white cheddar, the patties are sandwiched between potato buns with caramelized onion and a homemade special sauce that’s also perfect for pairing with Old Bay fries on the side—and will elicit major “oohs” and “ahhs” from your dining companions.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/6419b2b9f4ecf26bed0bd81b-8040bfea.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/64ad623c08c61453c499a919.pdf
time required: 35 minutes
author: Sara Heilman
cuisine: North America
course: main course
nutrition:
  calories: 1080 kcal
  fat: 65 g
  saturated fat: 23 g
  carbohydrates: 87 g
  sugar: 17 g
  protein: 37 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 1820 mg
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/cheesy-smashed-burgers-64ad623c08c61453c499a919
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of oil and half the @OLD BAY® Seasoning{1%unit} (you'll use more later). Season lightly with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: No need to season generously—there's already salt and pepper in the seasoning!

Roast on top rack until browned and crispy, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While potatoes roast, heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon} in a #medium pan{}, preferably nonstick, over medium-high heat. Add onion; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Add @sugar{1%teaspoon} (2 tsp for 4 servings) and a splash of water; cook until onion is caramelized and jammy, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #small bowl{}.

Meanwhile, in a second small bowl, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @ketchup{1%unit}, @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, and as much remaining Old Bay Seasoning as you like. Set aside.

Form @ground beef{10%ounce} into two equal-size balls (four balls for 4 servings); season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for onion over medium-high heat. Once pan is hot, add beef. Firmly flatten each ball with a #spatula{} to create very thin patties. (TIP: Do so carefully; oil may splatter a bit.) Cook to desired doneness, ~{3-4%minutes} per side. (Don't worry if the patties aren't perfectly round—those irregular edges will turn crispy.)

In the last ~{1-2%minutes} of cooking, top patties with @white cheddar cheese{1/2%cup}; cover pan to melt cheese. Remove from heat.

While patties cook, halve and toast @potato buns{2}.

Divide buns between plates and fill with patties, caramelized onion, and half the special sauce. Serve burgers with Old Bay fries on the side and remaining special sauce for dipping.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.